  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions spans several decades and involves international cooperation to combat financial crimes. Here's an overview:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal money laundering practices existed historically\n- Prohibition emerged primarily in response to organized crime activities\n\n2. United States Developments:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First major anti-money laundering (AML) legislation\n- Introduced reporting requirements for financial transactions\n- Established framework for tracking suspicious financial activities\n\n3. International Progression:\n- 1980s: Growing international recognition of money laundering as a global issue\n- FATF (Financial Action Task Force) established in 1989\n- Developed international standards for combating financial crimes\n\n4. Major Legislative Milestones:\n- US Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- US Comprehensive Crime Control Act (1984)\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) - Significantly expanded AML regulations\n\n5. Global Regulatory Framework:\n- United Nations conventions\n- Basel Committee recommendations\n- International cooperation through information sharing\n\n6. Recent Trends:\n- Increased digital currency regulations\n- Enhanced technological tracking mechanisms\n- Expanding definitions of financial crimes\n\nThe legal landscape continues evolving to address emerging financial technologies and sophisticated laundering techniques.",
